[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] In computer science, a **circular buffer**, **circular queue**, **cyclic buffer** or **ring buffer** is a data structure that uses a single, fixed-size buffer as if it were connected end-to-end.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] This structure lends itself easily to buffering data streams.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] There were early circular buffer implementations in hardware.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] A circular buffer first starts out empty and has a set length.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] If two elements are removed, the two oldest values inside of the circular buffer would be removed.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] Circular buffers use FIFO (*first in, first out*) logic.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] In the example, 1 & 2 were the first to enter the circular buffer, they are the first to be removed, leaving 3 inside of the buffer.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] When elements get removed, only the read-pointer moves to the next element.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] Removed elements are still in the buffer, waiting to get overwritten by new elements.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] A property of the circular buffer is that when it is full and a subsequent write is performed, then it starts overwriting the oldest data.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] Alternatively, the routines that manage the buffer could prevent overwriting the data and return an error or raise an exception.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] Whether or not data is overwritten is up to the semantics of the buffer routines or the application using the circular buffer.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] The useful property of a circular buffer is that it does not need to have its elements shuffled around when one is consumed.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] (If a non-circular buffer were used then it would be necessary to shift all elements when one is consumed.) In other words, the circular buffer is well-suited as a FIFO (*first in, first out*) buffer while a standard, non-circular buffer is well suited as a LIFO (*last in, first out*) buffer.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] Circular buffering makes a good implementation strategy for a queue that has fixed maximum size.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] Should a maximum size be adopted for a queue, then a circular buffer is a completely ideal implementation; all queue operations are constant time.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] However, expanding a circular buffer requires shifting memory, which is comparatively costly.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] For arbitrarily expanding queues, a linked list approach may be preferred instead.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] In some situations, an overwriting circular buffer can be used, e.g. in multimedia.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] If the buffer is used as the bounded buffer in the producer–consumer problem then it is probably desired for the producer (e.g., an audio generator) to overwrite old data if the consumer (e.g., the sound card) is unable to momentarily keep up.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] Also, the LZ77 family of lossless data compression algorithms operates on the assumption that strings seen more recently in a data stream are more likely to occur soon in the stream.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] Implementations store the most recent data in a circular buffer.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] In the beginning the indexes end and start are set to 0.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] The circular buffer write operation writes an element to the end index position and the end index is incremented to the next buffer position.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] The circular buffer read operation reads an element from the start index position and the start index is incremented to the next buffer position.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] The start and end indexes alone are not enough to distinguish between buffer full or empty state while also utilizing all buffer slots, but can be if the buffer only has a maximum in-use size of Length − 1.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] In this case, the buffer is empty if the start and end indexes are equal and full when the in-use size is Length − 1.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] Another solution is to have another integer count that is incremented at a write operation and decremented at a read operation.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] Then checking for emptiness means testing count equals 0 and checking for fullness means testing count equals Length.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] The following source code is a C implementation together with a minimal test.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] Function put() puts an item in the buffer, function get() gets an item from the buffer.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] A circular-buffer implementation may be optimized by mapping the underlying buffer to two contiguous regions of virtual memory.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] When the read offset is advanced into the second virtual-memory region, both offsets—read and write—are decremented by the length of the underlying buffer.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] Perhaps the most common version of the circular buffer uses 8-bit bytes as elements.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] Some implementations of the circular buffer use fixed-length elements that are bigger than 8-bit bytes—16-bit integers for audio buffers, 53-byte ATM cells for telecom buffers, etc.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] Each item is contiguous and has the correct data alignment, so software reading and writing these values can be faster than software that handles non-contiguous and non-aligned values.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] Ping-pong buffering can be considered a very specialized circular buffer with exactly two large fixed-length elements.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] The *bip buffer* (bipartite buffer) is very similar to a circular buffer, except it always returns contiguous blocks which can be variable length.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] This offers nearly all the efficiency advantages of a circular buffer while maintaining the ability for the buffer to be used in APIs that only accept contiguous blocks.
[src:dancing-links/circular-buffer] Fixed-sized compressed circular buffers use an alternative indexing strategy based on elementary number theory to maintain a fixed-sized compressed representation of the entire data sequence.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] In computer science, **dancing links** (**DLX**) is a technique for adding and deleting a node from a circular doubly linked list.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] It is particularly useful for efficiently implementing backtracking algorithms, such as Knuth's Algorithm X for the exact cover problem.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] Algorithm X is a recursive, nondeterministic, depth-first, backtracking algorithm that finds all solutions to the exact cover problem.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] Some of the better-known exact cover problems include tiling, the *n* queens problem, and Sudoku.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] will restore *x'*s position in the list, assuming that x.right and x.left have been left unmodified.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] This works regardless of the number of elements in the list, even if that number is 1.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] Knuth observed that a naive implementation of his Algorithm X would spend an inordinate amount of time searching for 1's.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] When selecting a column, the entire matrix had to be searched for 1's.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] When selecting a row, an entire column had to be searched for 1's.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] After selecting a row, that row and a number of columns had to be searched for 1's.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] To improve this search time from complexity O(n) to O(1), Knuth implemented a sparse matrix where only 1's are stored.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] At all times, each node in the matrix will point to the adjacent nodes to the left and right (1's in the same row), above and below (1's in the same column), and the header for its column (described below).
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] Each row and column in the matrix will consist of a circular doubly-linked list of nodes.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] Each column will have a special node known as the "column header," which will be included in the column list, and will form a special row ("control row") consisting of all the columns which still exist in the matrix.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] Finally, each column header may optionally track the number of nodes in its column, so that locating a column with the lowest number of nodes is of complexity O(*n*) rather than O(*n*×*m*) where *n* is the number of columns and *m* is the number of rows.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] Selecting a column with a low node count is a heuristic which improves performance in some cases, but is not essential to the algorithm.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] In Algorithm X, rows and columns are regularly eliminated from and restored to the matrix.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] Eliminations are determined by selecting a column and a row in that column.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] If a selected column doesn't have any rows, the current matrix is unsolvable and must be backtracked.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] When an elimination occurs, all columns for which the selected row contains a 1 are removed, along with all rows (including the selected row) that contain a 1 in any of the removed columns.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] The columns are removed because they have been filled, and the rows are removed because they conflict with the selected row.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] To remove a single column, first remove the selected column's header.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] Next, for each row where the selected column contains a 1, traverse the row and remove it from other columns (this makes those rows inaccessible and is how conflicts are prevented).
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] Repeat this column removal for each column where the selected row contains a 1.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] This order ensures that any removed node is removed exactly once and in a predictable order, so it can be backtracked appropriately.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] If the resulting matrix has no columns, then they have all been filled and the selected rows form the solution.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] To backtrack, the above process must be reversed using the second algorithm stated above.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] One requirement of using that algorithm is that backtracking must be done as an exact reversal of eliminations.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] Knuth's paper gives a clear picture of these relationships and how the node removal and reinsertion works, and provides a slight relaxation of this limitation.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] It is also possible to solve one-cover problems in which a particular constraint is optional, but can be satisfied no more than once.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] Dancing links accommodates these with primary columns which must be filled and secondary columns which are optional.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] This alters the algorithm's solution test from a matrix having no columns to a matrix having no primary columns and if the heuristic of minimum one's in a column is being used then it needs to be checked only within primary columns.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] Knuth discusses optional constraints as applied to the *n* queens problem.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] The chessboard diagonals represent optional constraints, as some diagonals may not be occupied.
[src:dancing-links/dancing-links] If a diagonal is occupied, it can be occupied only once.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] In computer science, a **double-ended queue** (abbreviated to **deque** — /dɛk/ *DEK*), is an abstract data type that serves as a container, with a restricted access to the stored items.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] As a generalization of both the stack and the queue, the deque may have similar functions as a data buffer: it can be use both as a *retainer* (queue), or for backtracking (stack).
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] However it offers greater flexibility in managing the order of elements and some algorithms are based on its functionalities.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] The double-ended queue is most often presented as a generalized queue, which gives its name.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] It is a queue that "allows insertions and deletions at both ends".
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] The deque is also described as a generalization of the stack abstract data structure, as "two stacks joined together at the base", with a shared bottom item, or as a combination of both the stack and the queue.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] And then conversely the queue and the stack are restricted forms of the deque.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Different analogies with real-world objects are used to described the deque.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] It is compared to a "deck of cards" with which the structure shares some properties and the pronunciation.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] The deque is also likened to a "necklace with beads that can be added and/or removed at either end".
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Like the queue, it is depicted as a set of items lined up in a pipe open at both ends ; unlike the queue, the items can move in both direction in the pipe.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] The "railroad model" introduced by Knuth (after "Dijkstra's shunting yard") focus on the similarity with the queue, with one input and one output, and switches to select the side of the deque to be accessed.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] The main operations on a deque are said to act on either *side* (or *end*) of the structure: addition of an item into the collection (*enqueue*), removal of an item *(dequeue*), and reading of an item (*peek*).
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] At at a given point in time only two items can be accessed, from either side of the deque, based on the history of the structure.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] The designated item on one side is either the latest one that has been inserted on this side (LIFO behavior), or, — if there is none —, the oldest one that has been inserted on the other side (FIFO behavior).
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] This service policy gives the structure more flexibility and versatility, but it is also more difficult to fathom and use.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Each approach has its merits: the first one allows the overloading of the operations but needs to have different names on each sides, while the second one simplifies the interface by halving the number of operations and allows to make use of the symmetry of the structure.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Despite their limitations these sub-types have many applications and some of their implementations may be simpler.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] After Knuth, these structures are often described as different forms of restricted *linear lists* , or sequences.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] They maintain the contained elements in a given order while only allow access to some of them: the first one and/or the last one in the sequence.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] However other authors object that they "hide their internal dynamism from the user" and only the common implementations are linear.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] For example, a deque can be implemented with a min-max heap, or with a set: before an item is inserted, it is tagged with a integer used as its value in the heap, and that depends on the history of the container.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] The stored elements in a heap are not ordered and their locations depend on the internal state of the structure.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Another common restricted access structure is the priority queue, which is not a linear structure.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] The deque can be generalized by the addition of some operations: a deque with heap order, or *mindeque*, allows the *find-min* operation.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Fast or even optimal catenation is also possible.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Some authors consider the deque structure as being of little use, less useful than its restricted forms, especially the stack and the queue.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] The deque can then be seen "as either a superqueue or a superstack".
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] "If two nodes are inserted at one end and removed from the other, they will exit in queue order.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] If they are both removed from the entry end, then they exit in stack order.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] "a data structure looking for an application!", cited by Roy S.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] The deque is here considered as unbounded: it can contain an unlimited (and undefined) number of items.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] A bounded deque is possible, and requires a slightly different specification, but when an overflow occurs the behavior depends on the implementation: error value, exception, deletion, etc.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] As a linear structure, the deque can be specified in terms of catenation (noted "~") of sequences and singleton sequences (noted "< ... >").
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] An axiomatic specification (or algebraic) of the deque can be obtained by extending and merging those of the stack and the queue.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] (see Nguyen thesis for an alternative formulation).
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Conversely the stack and the queue can be specified axiomatically in terms of the deque.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] The term *deque* (/dɛk/ *DEK*) is used as an abbreviation of Double-Ended QUEue.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] *Dequeue* is sometimes used but can be confusing as the term is also used for the operation of removing an element of the deque.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] A deque may also be called a *head-tail linked list*, though properly this refers to a specific implementation.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] An output-restricted deque may be designated as *steque* (for stack-ended queue).
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] There is no standard vocabulary associated with deques.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] The terms *enqueue* and *dequeue*, borrowed from the queue structure, generally denote the basic operations on a deque, on either end.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] But papers and actual implementations often use different names.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Unlike the associated data structures the deque is symmetrical.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] The full name of an operation may be a combination of the name of the basic operation and the name of the side: e.g.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Terms from different analogies may be associated in a single context: *append* and *pop*, *push* and *shift*, or *front* and *tail*.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Finally some programming languages use even different names based on the underlying data structure.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Also generally implemented are *"peek"* operations, which return the value at one end without dequeuing it.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] It is often named after the target side: e.g.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] *top* is the value of the element at the top of the deque.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] In the context of the functional programming, the *dequeue* operation (that returns two values: the removed element and the new deque) is not used.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] It is replaced by a *peek* function (i.e.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] *head* and *last*) and a function that returns the deque minus the end, i.e.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] There are at least two common ways to efficiently implement a deque, that are often pitted against one another: with a doubly linked list or with a modified dynamic array.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] There are many variations and actual implementations are often hybrid solutions.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Additionally, several purely functional implementations of the double-ended queue exist.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] While a simple list may implement a deque, a doubly-linked list is more adequate for its symmetry to achieve a fast access to both ends of the list (*head* and *tail*, hence the name *head-tail linked list*).
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] The obvious solution is to manage two references; alternatively the deque can be built as a circular list.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] In a doubly-linked list implementation, and assuming no allocation/deallocation overhead, the time complexity of all deque operations is O(1).
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Additionally, insertion or deletion in the middle, given an iterator, can also be achieved in constant time; however, the time taken for random access by index is O(n).
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Similarly, finding a specific element normally requires O(n) time.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Linked data structures generally have poor locality of reference.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] In this case as well, while a dynamic array can be used to implement a deque, a variant that can grow from both ends is more appropriate.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] This is sometimes called *array deques*.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] The *amortized* time complexity of all deque operations with an *array deque* is O(1), thanks to the geometric expansion of the back-end buffer.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Additionally, random access by index takes constant time ; but the average time taken for insertion or deletion in the middle are O(n).
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Thank to the fast random access, finding an element in an ordered array is time O(log n) (binary search).
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Each time the array is resized, the whole content is moved: the memory usage is then momentarily doubled (or more), and all direct (external) references to the content of the array are lost.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Doubly linked lists cannot be used as immutable data structures.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] And an immutable array would be highly inefficient (an array is often simulated by a tree).
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] A purely functional implementation of the deque can be based on stack, that is easily implemented with a singly linked list as an immutable and persistent structure.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] "Persistent lists with catenation via recursive slow-down".
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] *Proc. of the 27th annual ACM symposium on Theory of computing*.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] This last process could be rather complicated as it needs to be executed concurrently with other operations and completed before the next one, to achieve an amortized real-time complexity.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] The next step is to support the operations in O(1) *worst-case* time.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Another challenge is the real-time catenation of deques.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Okasaki gives a simple solution that uses lazy lists combined with memoization.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] The stack to stack balancing is then partially automatic by means of a precise scheduling of incremental functions.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] However some authors deem such algorithm as not purely functional since memoization is considered as a side effect.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] In this paper Kaplan and Tarjan also present an even more complex version that achieves catenation in real-time.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] However this description is mostly textual.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Pottier publish a verified implementation of this data structure (in OCaml and Rocq), alongside a formal description and detailed analysis of the algorithm.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] More generally, real-time catenation requires a deque is a tuple consisting mainly in two sub-structures, that themselves contain deques or compounds of deques.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] The linear spine of the non-catenable deque is then replaced by a *binary skeleton*.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Kaplan, Okasaki, and Tarjan produced a simpler, amortized version that can be implemented either using lazy evaluation or more efficiently using mutation in a broader but still restricted fashion.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Mihaescu and Tarjan created a simpler (but still highly complex) strictly purely functional implementation of catenable deques, and also a much simpler implementation of strictly purely functional non catenable deques, both of which have optimal worst-case bounds (not officially published).
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Ada's containers provides the generic packages `Ada.Containers.Vectors` and `Ada.Containers.Doubly_Linked_Lists`, for the dynamic array and linked list implementations, respectively.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] C++'s Standard Template Library provides the class templates `std::deque` and `std::list`, for the multiple array and linked list implementations, respectively.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] As of Java 6, Java's Collections Framework provides a new `Deque` interface that provides the functionality of insertion and removal at both ends.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] It is implemented by classes such as `ArrayDeque` (also new in Java 6) and `LinkedList`, providing the dynamic array and linked list implementations, respectively.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] However, the `ArrayDeque`, contrary to its name, does not support random access.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] JavaScript's Array prototype & Perl's arrays have native support for both removing (shift and pop) and adding (unshift and push) elements on both ends.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Python 2.4 introduced the `collections` module with support for deque objects.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] It is implemented using a doubly linked list of fixed-length subarrays.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] As of PHP 5.3, PHP's SPL extension contains the 'SplDoublyLinkedList' class that can be used to implement Deque datastructures.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] Previously to make a Deque structure the array functions array_shift/unshift/pop/push had to be used instead.
[src:dancing-links/double-ended-queue] GHC's Data.Sequence module implements an efficient, functional deque structure in Haskell.
